segments.text: an unfortunate personality.
You've met people like that.
They just couldn't seem to get along with anybody.
And the last month or two of school, we'd just, somebody every night would drown that old boy out.
And it was downright shameful.
And I've...
I've been ashamed all my life of doing it, but at the time it was an awful lot of fun.
It's a great deal more fun to bedevil somebody when you get an adverse reaction.
That's right.
If you just take it in stride, it's not really a great deal of fun.

That's right, and normally most of the people would get drowned out once a year or once or twice in the spring, and they'd take it good naturally and say, okay, we're going to get tomorrow night, and they'd leave him alone.
But that type of a person, everybody would concentrate on him.
And it was, I don't know why he didn't get webbed feet as much as he was drafted out.
But there wasn't as much of that.
Now there was a little of it over in the non-military.
Somebody that you didn't like and you wanted to mess them up.
Well, there's nothing much worse than a big bucket of water and a cot and a bed and a mattress because there ain't no going back to bed.
The rest of the night you sit up and it's a lot of fun.

and it's it's we got to where this old boy we drowned out we go in and wake him up and just he's set up we let him have it oh lord lord what kids won't do there's not in the book what was the food like in the mess hall i thought it was delightful i never did have a complaint about the food a lot of kids a lot of men boys
complained about it.

They said it wasn't any good, it was dirty, and the truth of the matter, the food was delicious, it was nutritious, and there wasn't a boy that ever went to A&M College that didn't grow fat and husky and healthy on the food.
But as you could understand, preparing it in the quantities they did, certainly it didn't have the touch that Mama did at home.
And naturally, there'd be some
bitching about it, griping about it, but I never did feel that way about the food.
In fact, I ate better at A&M than I had all my life because I ate well at home, but I worked like the devil, too.
I mean, in the field, hard, and so I had no complaint about the food.
I thought it was wonderful.
Was there much variety, or did you have
Oh, I thought we had a lot of variety.
Now that there, I think, is part of the trouble.
It was kind of a monotonous menu.
In other words, on Monday you had this, Tuesday you had this, Wednesday you had this, Thursday and Friday you had this, and Saturday and Sunday.
And you could almost sit down and write the menu for the whole week.
And it did get monotonous in that sense.
Well, it wasn't because it wasn't good or well-prepared or nutritious.
You just kind of get tired of it.
So if you could rake up a few extra dimes, you'd go over to Agland every now and then and have a meal that you ordered yourself, what you wanted, where you wanted.
It wouldn't be a bit better food, but it's something you sat down and ordered and ate because you wanted it instead of having it set in front of you.
Psychological dislike more than any actual dislike.
Let's see, was your freshman year would have been the year after Harold Dunn had the hamburger stand, wasn't it?
I went there in the fall of 26.
Did Harold have a...
He had it in 24 and 25 is when he had the hamburger stand.
Well, I was going to say Harold is a class of 25, if I'm not mistaken.
So he was gone.
He told me, I believe, that...
athletic department took over the hamburger stand.
I think so.
So it was still there when you were there?
Well, now, Pop, uh, Pop, uh, the old man that ran a hamburger joint over there himself, he ran it.
I don't know whether he was running it for the athletic department or who.
Pop, uh, sir.
I should remember that name, because that's where a lot of us, when we get an extra dime and didn't want to go to the mess hall, we'd go get a hamburger with Pops.
And I can't think of his last name, because Pops is the only way I've ever called him.
No, Harold was, I believe, a class of 25, because I met him after I moved to Lubbock.
Okay.
Did the...
Non-military students ate in the same mess hall then with the military students for the last three years?
In the mess hall, yeah.
They didn't eat together.
They had tables in a different area because they came in from another door.
Most of the military came in from the, well, towards Gine Hall, down that way, and the non-military came in from the side over there.
They ate in the same mess hall but not at a different table.
See, all the companies ate together.
They had assigned sections where they ate and they all ate there the whole year.
And so did the non-military.
We'd eat at the same place.
What privileges did the upperclassmen have over the freshmen?
Well, there wasn't many privileges that the freshmen had that wasn't authorized by the upperclassmen.
But to me, it was a pretty equitable system because the sophomores were controlled by the juniors and the seniors.
The juniors were controlled by the seniors.
The seniors were controlled by the senior officers in the military.
So you had kind of a line of command there.
There wasn't any particular area that you could be mistreated.
As I say, there's nothing lower in the world than a freshman unless it's a sophomore.
Now, sophomore is the lowest creature on the campus, at least it used to be considered.
Freshman, he'd get by with ignorance, didn't know when he really did know, but he could get by with it.
He might get his pants whomped, but he could still get by with doing things that a sophomore or junior couldn't because they knew better.

But the sophomores were kept in line primarily by the seniors, and the juniors themselves were pretty well kept in line by the seniors because I've seen many a junior get his rear end whipped by a senior for doing something that the senior didn't think he should do.
So hazing wasn't confined to freshmen.
It was all classes.
All classes except the seniors.
That's right.
Well, the seniors were harassed and heckled by their own fellow officers and the military.
They weren't actually Hays, but they had some degree of control over even them.
No, the freshman really was the...

lucky one on the campus because ignorance is not supposed to be an excuse for violating the law but many many of them do so well i didn't know any better i i thought you could do that and with the sophomore he'd get in trouble every time he'd do anything wrong so
What about privileges to leave the campus?
Did the upperclassmen have the privilege to do that more frequently?
Oh, yes.
The juniors and the seniors, as I recall, could leave any time they wanted to.
And the juniors could most of the time they wanted to.
And the sophomores, less often.
And of course, the freshmen could not leave without specific permission, as I recall.
I don't think I went to Bryan my freshman year.
How would you have gotten to Bryan?
Tuneville Trolley.
Had the old trolley, yeah.
It ran until, I think, a couple of years after I got out of there.
See me like 27 or 8 or 9.
I'm not sure when they took the old trolley off.
What about your last three years there when you were non-military?
Did you have more privileges as a non-military student than, say, the military students did?
Well, it seems to me that we did.
We had less restrictions.
We were, as a civilian, the two years that I was in the non-military but did not wear a uniform, we pretty well came and went as we wanted to.
We'd go to Bryan or go to Houston.
Now, I don't mean we could miss class or anything like that, but if it was a holiday or a weekend, we could go where we wanted to with no particular problem.
But...
And even in the military, you could, I believe it was your junior and senior year.
In other words, just the two first years that you were partially restricted to your dorm or to staying on the campus.
But then the last year when you were non-military but you had to wear a uniform, were you more under military control then?
No, they had nothing to do with us.
We had no drilling or nothing.
It was a means purely of identification.
I think some of the military people got envious of our civilian clothes and said, well, golly, they ought to be in uniform, too.
But, you know, my senior year, when I had to wear a uniform,
to meals and to classes.
I had one shirt and one pair of pants.
That's all I owned that year.
I had a blue serge, I mean not a blue serge, but a serge khaki shirt and a nice pair of slacks, and that's the only uniform I had all year.
So even in the non-military where you were required to wear a uniform, you didn't have quite the expense or the uniforms that juniors and seniors require.
At that point, was it a fairly universal thing for the seniors to wear the kind of boots that the seniors wear now, or did only the senior officers wear the boots?
Everybody, every senior could wear them.
The juniors, I mean the seniors, were the only ones that could wear boots, and of course
Well, let's see.
We went into, or the military went into slacks.
I know the first year, my freshman year, we wore those old wrap leggings because I despised them.
I think that's one thing that got me out of the military, wrapping that legging every morning.
And it seems to me that we went, uh, the second year, no, by golly, the second year we had, uh,
either leggings or wrap leggings, you know, these leather inside leggings or the wraps.
I believe both years, it seems to me.
But I think then my junior or senior year, when I was out of the Corps, it seemed to me like they went to slacks, but I'm not sure about the timing on that.
I know my sophomore year, I won the best drill medal in my Company D infantry, and we were wearing those
laced leggings.
You know, you lace them up the side.
I'm sure you've seen it.
And I think we had quit the old wrap leggings and gone to those, and then I believe it was the third year I was at A&M that they went to slacks, but I could be wrong.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
I believe one of my favorites down there was C.O.
Spriggs.
I believe he was in the English department and taught public speaking.
And I took public speaking as an elective, and I just thoroughly enjoyed the way he handled his courses.
In other words, in teaching public speaking,
He didn't have the usual format of a book and assignments and lessons.
You were kind of on your own.
And he'd make you make impromptu speeches and tell of some happening.
You know, it kind of gets you familiar with standing on your feet.
And I liked the general lack of formality, I believe.
Now, I had some math teachers that I thoroughly enjoyed, Mr. Martin.
My sophomore year, I believe it was, I was taking calculus.
Yeah, Mr. Martin lived in Bryan.
Incidentally, I bought his house in 1943.
He was a mathematical wizard in my mind, and I thoroughly enjoyed him.
He's the only reason I probably passed calculus, because I flunked it the first time I took it.
And the second time I passed it, and only because he was such an excellent teacher.
He could just make you get it whether you wanted it or not.
And I guess he was one of my favorites.
And Mr. Mitchell, A. Mitchell, that taught engineering, no, descriptive geometry, A. Mitchell.
His son lives there in Bryan, or at least I guess he still does, Scripp Mitchell.
I guess those would be about my three favorite teachers that I recall because not only subject matter but the way they handled their subject matter.
Did you have any people in your engineering courses in particular that you felt Like or dislike?
Well, I like Si Sanstead, I believe, as well as him.
Si's still there, isn't he, incidentally?
I believe he's retired.
Oh, yes, Lord, he's retired.
He's close to 90 years old.
I believe he's still living.
He's old as the college.
But he was one of my favorites.
Sleepy Sanstead, they called him.
Because he'd give you a quiz and sit up there and doze in his chair.
We called him Sleepy.
But he was an awful, awful nice man, a good instructor.

and uh last uh last time I saw him he was still active as he could be and now he's been retired in fact he retired from teaching before I moved up here in 58. so he's bound to be in his 80s he's not far from 90 years old yeah well I think even then the compulsory retirement was 70 so yeah so he's he's up well up in his 80s I'm pretty sure and
Of course, Mr. Ritchie, the head of the Civil Engineering Department, and J.T.L.
McNew were two more favorites, and I guess you might say I had three favorites in the C.E.
Department because J.T.L.
McNew taught highway engineering, and by the time I was a junior, well, my third, fourth, and fifth years, or the last two years, I knew I was working towards highway engineering.
and J.T.L.
McNew taught that and I liked him.

He's a very practical man down to earth and he didn't care what the book said always if the book didn't tell it like it was out on the job because he worked for the public a lot in the summer and he was an excellent instructor.
What were the attitudes of the students overall toward the administration?
I think they had a tremendous lot of respect for the administration in general.

It seems to me, of course, I'm sure this is a thing that everybody feels, as you get older you feel like the younger people don't have the respect for the administration or the people in authority that you had when you were young.
But I think as a whole, the students were pretty respectful and held in high esteem, most of the administration.
Because most of the administration, so far as we knew as students and campus life, were pretty well above approach.
And I'm sure they weren't because everybody's human and everybody gets their foot in their mouth occasionally.
But you didn't hear much about it.
It wasn't discussed among the students, and in general, they had a pretty high respect for him, I think.
The president was who?
Thomas Otto Van Waltenburg.
Theo Walton.
He was a fine man.
And was the same respect accorded to the commandant?
Well, there was a little bit of, let's say, kind of a...

slurring remarks made about the bull, the commandant, I guess because just general resentment toward authority, because you looked at the military as authority, and everybody rebels to some extent to authority at one time or another.
So there was a little less now outwardly and
in fact, to the Commandant's Office, everybody was pretty respectful because they were scared not to be.
But there was a little more slurring remarks and catty statements about so-and-so and so-and-so in the military than there was in the civilian administration, it seemed to me.
See, I mentioned at the time you were there, there were at least, what, probably two Commandants.
Didn't they come generally for two years?
No.
As I recall, they were assigned for four years, I thought, because Colonel Nelson...

Well, actually, he's the only commandant I remember because he was there, I think, my two freshman years, or I mean my first two years while I was in the military, and maybe the third year when I got in non-military.
I don't know.
Colonel Nelson is the only name I can recall while I was in school as competent, let's put it that way.
Now, whether he was there two years or three years, I really don't know.
But I was thinking they were assigned there for four years.
I'm not quite certain about the time that you were there.
It seems to me that there was a time period at least.
earlier than that, that the commandant was a two-year hitch.
Well, now, you could very well be right.
I think there were some who got a renewal, so to speak, and stayed more than two.
But anyway.
One thing that's of some interest currently is perhaps less an issue now than a few years back, and that is a matter of girls on campus.
And we know that there was a time period when there were a few girls, and then there was none.
And now, of course, we have lots of them.
Were there any girls in any of the classes when you were there?
In that particular period, as I recall, there were no girls in school, except now they could go to summer school.
If you went to summer school, there would be girls in classes in summer.
So far as I can remember, ever since I can remember anything about A&M, girls could go to summer school.
There was no restriction on summer school, as I recall.
There was no military.
That's right, no military activity going on then.
But there were no girls in any of the classes through the regular term during my period down there, and I don't think there had been for six, eight, or ten years.
It seems to me some of the professors' daughters graduated there, and I've seen in the histories somewhere, archives somewhere, and you probably know more about that.
There was one or two who actually graduated from A&M years and years ago.
But then for a long period in there,
All they could do was go in summers, I recall.
At the time that you were there, did the students who participated in intercollegiate athletics enjoy any special privileges?
Oh, to some extent, I think you could say they did, because any notable individual is given certain... Oh...

limits or limitations or less limitations on behavior probably than just an ordinary student because that's part of the essence of of notoriety they they just actually but so far as the actual uh privileges all i know of they had a special eating place they ate uh
a little better, supposedly, and I used to remember that they got all the milk they wanted.
Now, that's the one thing that stands out in my mind, because I loved milk, and we never had enough milk at the regular table.
But at the training table, they gave them all the milk they wanted.
And outside of that, I don't think there was any particular special food or anything.
It was sometime after you were there then that they had a separate athletic dormitory.
Oh, yeah.
In fact, it was in the 40s, it seems to me, after the war.
I don't know when it was.
Yeah.
Didn't old Bear Bryant get the first dormitory built or it started in his regime or had they just built it when Bear Bryant came there in the 50s?

I think it was earlier than that that they had to put them all, took them out of their military company and put them in the Well, they may have, but I remember Henderson Hall, and I was thinking that was built about the time Barry Bryant came there in the early 50s, but I'm not sure of that.
I mean, I believe that they were separated.
Well, they probably were, probably were.
Okay.
were any number of the athletes non-military for the last two years?
Quite a few.
I remember old Joel Hunt was, and as I recall, it seems to me Joel and one or two other of the football players went into the non-military.
In other words, they didn't want to be bothered with drilling and so forth.
Now, I'm not even positive about that, Charles, because as I say, I didn't associate, didn't know them, and I just knew of them.
When you finished A&M then, did you have a job lined up before you graduated?
In 1931, Charles, there wasn't any jobs anywhere.
If you remember, that was the bottom of the well.
No, I was pretty desperate because I had gotten my degree.
I couldn't go home without a job because I was the first one in all of my family history that had ever gone to college.

And to go home without a job after going to college, I just, well, I told somebody there in Bryan after I finally went to work, I said, I'd have started robbing before I'd have gone home and admitted I didn't have a job after getting a college degree.
But I finally managed to get a job there in Bryan with the highway department because I think I got the man's attention.
I was so desperate that I offered to work.
I told Mr. Todd, the man that I went to work for, he was a resident engineer there in Bryan.
I told him, I says, I will work one month for nothing.
just to prove to you how bad I need a job and that I will work.
Well, I'll never forget, he laughed and looked at me and he says, you know, I believe you want to work.
I said, Mr. Todd, you don't know how bad I want to work.
I meant every word I said.
I'll work for a month for nothing because I got to have a job.
I can't go home without a job.
Okay.
So I started to work for $3 a day.
Of course, he paid me.
He didn't let me work a month for nothing, but

I still think that that got his attention in the fact that, well, he does need to work, and they did need people in the highway department, but I didn't have any more chance than dozens of others who had been to see him.
But like the man with the mule, I think I got his attention.
What was your first position in with the highway department?
Rodman, they called me a rodman.
I drug a chain and held this line rod that they used to sight at and cut brush and drove stakes.
Laying out new highways.
Yep, staking a new highway or setting construction stakes for construction or rebuilding.
And that's where I started.
First to
June or around the first of June of 1931.
How long did you stay in the Bryan office then, the highway department?
I was in the Bryan district there for 28 years when I moved out here, 27 years I believe it was, from 1931 to 58, 27 years.
did they offer you then the opportunity to move to Lubbock, or did you request that?
No, the state highway engineer appointed me district engineer in Lubbock in 1958.
I had been through all of the positions in a district headquarters or office, including assistant district engineer.
And I had been assistant district engineer in Bryan for
Well, from 53 to the last of 57, about between four and five years.
And then Mr. Greer, who was a state Iowa engineer then, asked me if I would like to come to Lubbock as district engineer.
And I was like the idiot that went around on the drill field picking up pieces of paper until he found a paper that said, you are hereby discharged from the Army.
He says, this is the one I've been looking for.

And that job was the one I'd been looking for because to me it's the best job in the highway department and that's what I'd always aspired to be, a district engineer, so Santa Claus came to see me in 1958.
And so we moved to Lubbock and I worked for 15 years almost to a day because I moved here the first of February, 58, and retired
1st of February, 1973.
So almost, just almost a day, 15 years.
What would you say would be some of the principal developments in the last 40 years in highway construction?
I guess computerization of many of our calculations would
be the most drastic change because basically we're using the same type of materials to build roads we've always used.
Sand, gravel, caliche, crushed stone, cement, steel, you know, concrete.
We've been using that for 40 some odd years.
And your method of surveying aerial photography, computerization of many of our calculations of design of
intricate structures that used to take weeks and months of careful figuring and checking back to see that your calculations were correct.
Would this be calculations like on the cloverleaf?
Yeah.
And you also can use computers for determining elevations.
You've seen some of these four-level interchanges.
They call them mixmasters.
Well, all of the
Grades and elevations are computed with a computer.
By feeding certain information into it, it'll come out and give you the elevations of these various points on this Mixmaster looking thing.
Otherwise, it would be impossible to build some of the interchanges that they have today without computerization.
Just like without computers, it would have been impossible to go to the moon.
You just got to have it because you do the figuring of 100 people.
